Perfect! I found the issue. Looking at line 220 in Tag.java:
```java
private static final String[] preserveWhitespaceTags = {"pre", "plaintext", "title", "textarea"};
```

So the "title" tag IS in the preserveWhitespaceTags array, which means that when `titleEl.text()` is called, it will preserve the original whitespace instead of normalizing it, because the `preserveWhitespace()` method returns true for title tags.

Looking back at the `appendNormalisedText` method:
```java
if (!preserveWhitespace()) {
    text = TextNode.normaliseWhitespace(text);
    if (TextNode.lastCharIsWhitespace(accum))
        text = TextNode.stripLeadingWhitespace(text);
}
```

Since title tags preserve whitespace, the normalization doesn't happen! This is the bug. The `title()` method needs to normalize the whitespace even for title tags, despite them normally preserving whitespace for HTML output purposes.

Let me look at the `preserveWhitespace` method:

Now I understand the root cause. The `title()` method in Document.java currently does:

```java
public String title() {
    // title is a preserve whitespace tag (for document output), but normalised here
    Element titleEl = getElementsByTag("title").first();
    return titleEl != null ? titleEl.text().trim() : "";
}
```

The comment says "title is a preserve whitespace tag (for document output), but normalised here", but the actual implementation is not normalizing the text because title elements have `preserveWhitespace()` returning `true`, so the internal `appendNormalisedText` method does not normalize the text.

The fix is to apply the whitespace normalization manually in the `title()` method after getting the text.

